      <data key="d8">AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION RISK</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">COVID-19 mitigation strategies reduce the risk of airborne transmission in public and healthcare environments.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="WHO DIRECTOR-GENERAL'S OPENING REMARKS AT THE MEDIA BRIEFING ON COVID-19 - MARCH 11, 2020" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">WHO DIRECTOR-GENERAL'S OPENING REMARKS AT THE MEDIA BRIEFING ON COVID-19 - MARCH 11, 2020</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The WHO Director-General's remarks provide authoritative validation for the recognition of COVID-19 as a global airborne pathogen threat, justifying the implementation of engineering and operational controls in healthcare settings.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="WHO CORONAVIRUS DISEASE (COVID-19) DASHBOARD" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">WHO CORONAVIRUS DISEASE (COVID-19) DASHBOARD</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The WHO COVID-19 Dashboard tracks the global spread and impact of COVID-19, providing epidemiological evidence that supports the need for and effectiveness of airborne infection controls.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.6</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="MIC POPULATION CENSUS 2010 - AGGREGATION OF POPULATION AND INDUSTRY BY PLACE OF EMPLOYMENT AND SCHOOL" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">MIC POPULATION CENSUS 2010 - AGGREGATION OF POPULATION AND INDUSTRY BY PLACE OF EMPLOYMENT AND SCHOOL</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The MIC Population Census provides demographic and mobility data that supports modeling of COVID-19 transmission risk and validates the necessity of infection control measures in both community and hospital settings.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.5</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="MHLW VIEWS ON MEASURES AGAINST COVID-19, NOVEL CORONAVIRUS EXPERT MEETING" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">MHLW VIEWS ON MEASURES AGAINST COVID-19, NOVEL CORONAVIRUS EXPERT MEETING</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The MHLW expert meeting document provides policy-level validation for the implementation of engineering and operational controls targeting COVID-19 in healthcare and community settings.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CDC SCIENTIFIC BRIEF" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">CDC SCIENTIFIC BRIEF</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The CDC Scientific Brief summarizes scientific evidence on COVID-19 transmission and the effectiveness of controls, validating the use of engineering controls to reduce airborne transmission in hospitals.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AEROSOLS" target="COVID-19">
      <data key="d7">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19</data>
      <data key="d9">TARGETS</data>
      <data key="d10">Aerosols are the primary vector through which COVID-19 (SARS-CoV-2) is transmitted in indoor environments. Infection control measures targeting aerosols are thus directly aimed at reducing COVID-19 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AEROSOLS" target="HUMANS">
      <data key="d7">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d8">HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d9">APPLIED_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Aerosols are generated by and affect humans within hospital zones, serving as the primary vehicle for airborne transmission of pathogens between individuals. This relationship highlights the importance of controlling aerosols to protect human health in healthcare environments.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AIR POLLUTION, INDOOR" target="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">AIR POLLUTION, INDOOR</data>
      <data key="d8">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">Engineering controls that reduce indoor air pollution, such as improved ventilation and filtration, decrease the concentration of infectious aerosols in indoor environments.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HUMANS" target="CARBON DIOXIDE">
      <data key="d7">HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d8">CARBON DIOXIDE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DOSE</data>
      <data key="d10">Humans are the primary source of indoor carbon dioxide through respiration, and their presence and activity levels determine CO2 generation rates.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.5</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HUMANS" target="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d8">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DOSE</data>
      <data key="d10">Humans generate aerosols through breathing, talking, coughing, and other activities, contributing to the airborne transmission of pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.5</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">REDUCES</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation systems reduce the concentration of aerosols in indoor air by increasing air exchange and promoting dilution, thereby decreasing the risk of airborne transmission of pathogens carried in aerosols. This relationship is fundamental to infection control in healthcare and is supported by evidence linking improved ventilation to reduced airborne disease transmission.</data>
      <data key="d11">1.0</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="CARBON DIOXIDE">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">CARBON DIOXIDE</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DOSE</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation effectiveness is monitored and quantified using indoor carbon dioxide (CO2) levels. Lower CO2 concentrations indicate higher rates of outdoor air exchange, serving as a proxy for the operational rate of the ventilation control. This relationship is significant for real-time assessment and adjustment of ventilation to maintain safe indoor air quality.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
